# COMMIT DISCIPLINE

> This file is a binding rule for all contributors — human developers and AI agents alike.
> Every commit in this repository must follow these rules without exception.

---

## Why This Matters

This is a government asset management system. The git history is not just a development log — it is an operational record. Every change to this codebase must be:

- **Traceable** — anyone reading the history must understand what changed and why
- **Reviewable** — changes must be small enough to be reviewed meaningfully
- **Reversible** — any single commit must be safely revertible without taking down unrelated features
- **Deployable** — every commit must leave the codebase in a working, passing state

A bloated, vague, or bundled commit defeats all four of these goals. This is especially critical for AI agents, which tend to batch large amounts of work into a single commit — that behavior is explicitly prohibited here.

---

## The Core Rule

> **One commit = one meaningful unit of work, in a working state.**

A "meaningful unit of work" is the smallest change that:
- Has a single, describable purpose
- Does not break anything that was previously working
- Can be understood in isolation

---

## What Belongs in a Single Commit

Each of the following is a valid single commit. Never combine more than one of these in the same commit:

### Tooling and Configuration
- Installing and configuring one package (e.g., Tailwind CSS)
- Adding or updating a single configuration file (e.g., `vite.config.ts`, `.env.example`)
- Setting up a single CI/CD pipeline stage
- Adding a Docker service to `docker-compose.yml`

### Database
- Creating one database schema table
- Adding or modifying columns on one existing table
- Creating a new Drizzle migration
- Writing the TypeBox schema for one table
- Adding seed data for one entity type

### API
- Adding one API endpoint or one group of tightly related endpoints (e.g., CRUD for one resource)
- Adding middleware (e.g., RBAC permission check, rate limiter)
- Adding one Elysia plugin registration
- Writing tests for one API endpoint

### UI and Pages
- Adding one complete page (e.g., Login page, Asset Detail page)
- Adding one standalone reusable component
- Adding a single shadcn-svelte component installation
- Implementing one form with its validation and states

### Features
- Implementing one discrete feature end-to-end (e.g., "user invite flow", "session expiry on deactivation")
- Adding one dashboard card or widget
- Adding one report type
- Implementing one form draft auto-save

### Documentation and Rules
- Creating or updating one documentation file
- Creating or updating one plan file
- Creating or updating one rules file

### Fixes
- Fixing one specific bug with a reproducible cause
- Correcting one misconfiguration

---

## What Is NOT Allowed in a Single Commit

The following are prohibited. If you catch yourself doing any of these, split the commit:

- ❌ Multiple unrelated changes in one commit
- ❌ "Implementing auth and assets and the dashboard" in one commit
- ❌ Creating multiple database tables in one commit (unless they are a single migration that must be atomic)
- ❌ Mixing feature code with test code (test code should accompany the feature it tests, in the same commit — this is the one exception to "one thing only")
- ❌ Committing broken code with a note like "will fix later"
- ❌ Committing commented-out code, `console.log` debugging, or temporary hacks
- ❌ Committing without running `vp check` and `vp test` first

---

## Commit Message Format

This project follows [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/).

### Structure

```
<type>(<optional scope>): <short imperative description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

### Type Reference

| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | A new feature or capability |
| `fix` | A bug fix |
| `chore` | Maintenance that doesn't change behavior (deps, config, tooling) |
| `docs` | Documentation or rules files only |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring with no behavior change |
| `test` | Adding or updating tests with no production code change |
| `style` | Formatting only (should be rare since `vp check --fix` handles this) |
| `ci` | CI/CD pipeline changes |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

### Scope (optional but recommended)

Use scope to identify the system area affected:

```
feat(assets): add GET /api/v1/assets list endpoint
feat(auth): implement session expiry on user deactivation
fix(forms): handle 422 validation error on asset create
chore(deps): pin @sinclair/typebox to 0.32.4
docs(rbac): add role-permission matrix to RBAC_ROLES_AND_PERMISSIONS.md
```

### Description Rules

- Use the **imperative mood**: "add", "create", "fix", "remove", "update" — not "added", "adding", "adds"
- Lowercase first letter
- No period at the end
- Maximum 72 characters for the subject line
- Be specific enough that someone can understand the change without opening the diff

### Body (optional)

Use the body when the *why* is not obvious from the subject:

```
feat(auth): implement session expiry on user deactivation

When an admin deactivates a user account, all active sessions
for that user must be invalidated immediately server-side.
This prevents deactivated users from continuing to use the
system until their session naturally expires.

Closes #42
```

