## Branch Strategy

| Branch | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `main` | Production-ready code only. All CI/CD pipelines run on push. |
| `develop` | Integration branch. Features merge here before going to `main`. |
| `feature/<name>` | One feature per branch. Branch from `develop`. |
| `fix/<name>` | Bug fixes. Branch from `develop` (or `main` for hotfixes). |
| `docs/<name>` | Documentation-only changes. |
| `chore/<name>` | Tooling, config, dependency updates. |

### Branch naming examples

```
feature/asset-create-form
feature/physical-inventory-campaign
fix/pagination-offset-calculation
fix/session-expiry-on-deactivation
docs/rbac-permissions-matrix
chore/upgrade-elysia-to-1-2
```

---

## Merging

- Feature branches are merged via **Merge Requests (MRs)** on GitLab
- Direct pushes to `main` are prohibited
- All MR pipelines must pass (`vp check`, `vp test`, build) before merging
- Squash merging is **not** used — preserve the individual commits so history is readable
- Rebase onto the target branch before merging to keep history linear

---

## For AI Agents Specifically

AI agents working on this codebase must follow these additional rules:

1. **Never batch more than one feature into a single commit**, regardless of how related they seem
2. **Always run `vp check` and `vp test` before committing** — this is non-negotiable
3. **Do not commit to resolve your own context limit** — if you are running out of context, stop at a clean breakpoint, commit what is done and passing, and note where to resume
4. **Do not commit placeholder code** — if a function body is not implemented, do not commit `// TODO: implement this` and call the commit done
5. **Do not generate and commit test files separately from the feature they test** — tests travel with their feature in the same commit (this is the one bundling exception)
6. **Every commit message must be written as if a human will read it in six months** — be specific, be clear, be honest about what changed
